He wished to become a citizen of Heraclea, and since the people of Heraclea thought him worthy of this honor he was enrolled as a citizen. Not long after this when a law had been passed that no foreigner who was not a citizen should live at Rome, aman named Gratius said that Archias had not been legally enrolled, and tried to drive him out of the city. Cicero spolie in defenoe of the poet, and said that even if he were not a citizen he deserved to be made one. He also brought forward as a witness Lucius Lucullus, who said that he had been present when Archias was enrolled, and after this testi- mony had been heard, nobody doubted that Archias was a citizen.
